    "Task_1\n",
    "\n",
    "     > Download Python:\n",
    "\n",
    "        Go to the official Python website.\n",
    "        \n",
    "        Choose the version appropriate for your operating system (Windows, macOS, or Linux).\n",
    "        \n",
    "        Click on the Download button for the latest stable version (e.g., Python 3.10 or later).\n",
    "        \n",
    "     > Install Python:\n",
    "\n",
    "        Once the file is downloaded, run the installer.\n",
    "        Important: Make sure to check the box that says Add Python to PATH before clicking Install Now. \n",
    "        This ensures Python can be run from the command line easily.\n",
    "\n",
    "     > Verify Installation:\n",
    "\n",
    "        Type the following command to verify\n",
    "        python --version\n",
    "\n",
    "     > Setting up a Code Editor:\n",
    "\n",
    "        Download and Install Visual Studio Code (VS Code):\n",
    "\n",
    "        Go to the VS Code download page.\n",
    "        Download the version for your operating system (Windows, macOS, or Linux).\n",
    "        Install VS Code by following the installation prompts.\n",
    "        Install the Python Extension in VS Code:\n",
    "   \n",
    "      > Open VS Code after installation.\n",
    "\n",
    "        Go to the Extensions tab (the square icon on the left sidebar).\n",
    "        Search for “Python” and click on the first extension that appears (by Microsoft).\n",
    "        Click the Install button to install the Python extension.\n",
    "        Verify Python in VS Code:\n",
    " \n",
    "      > Open VS Code, and create a new Python file by clicking File > New File, then saving it with a .py extension.\n",
    "        In the file type the following command\n",
    "        print(\"Hello, World!\")\n",
    "\n",
    "        To run the code, open the Terminal in VS Code (`Ctrl+``), and type:\n",
    "        python hello_world.py\n",
    "\n",
    "Task_2\n",
    "\n",
    "      > You Need to know about Comments:\n",
    "        1. Single-line Comment\n",
    "           A single-line comment starts with a # symbol. Everything after the # on that line is considered a comment.\n",
    "           example:- # This is a single-line comment\n",
    "                     x = 10  # This is an inline comment\n",
    "\n",
    "        2. Multi-line Comment\n",
    "           Python doesn’t have a specific syntax for multi-line comments,\n",
    "           but you can use multiple single-line comments or use triple quotes (''' or \"\"\") to create multi-line comments.\n",
    "           example:- \"\"\"This is a multi-line comment.\n",
    "                        It can span several lines and can be used\n",
    "                        for detailed explanations.\"\"\"\n",
    "                        x = 10\n",
    "      > You need to know about indentation\n",
    "        -Indentation in Python refers to the spaces or tabs used at the beginning of a line of code to define the structure and hierarchy of the code.\n",
    "\n",
    "        Why Indentation is Important in Python:\n",
    "\n",
    "        -Defines code blocks: It helps Python understand which statements belong together. For example, inside a function or a loop.\n",
    "        -Improves readability: Proper indentation makes your code more readable and structured.\n"
   ]
  }
